Grafana Alert Routing to Internal Alert System
Dummy runbook v3 — generic JSON template on the existing SNS topic (pilot: Airflow CPU Utilization)

1. Purpose
Grafana alerts need to be sent to an internal alert system. The internal alert system receives events through a Lambda function created by the DaaS/internal alert system developer. Grafana must send alerts in a JSON format that the Lambda can parse and transform into the internal alert object.
This version defines one generic pattern that works for all (~260) Grafana alerts, including rules that do not define custom labels. It reuses the existing SNS topic — no new AWS resources are created. Email subscribers on the topic will receive the JSON body instead of the default Grafana text; the recipients are all developers and the team has accepted JSON-formatted alert emails. The Airflow CPU Utilization alert is used as the pilot.
2. Design Principles
One topic, one format. The existing topic keeps both its email subscribers and the SQS → Lambda subscription. The message body becomes strict JSON for everyone. The email subject line stays human-readable (Grafana's SNS integration has a separate Subject field), so inbox scanning still works.
Generic template. The contact point message template contains no alert-specific values. It serializes whatever labels and annotations each alert actually has. Every Grafana alert automatically carries at least the alertname and grafana_folder labels, so even rules with no custom labels produce a usable payload.
Tolerant Lambda. The Lambda treats all custom labels as optional and applies defaults or a lookup table when a label is missing. It also tolerates non-JSON bodies during the transition instead of crashing.
Gradual adoption. Teams add the standard label set to their rules over time. As labels appear, the Lambda's defaults are used less. No big-bang migration of 260 rules is required.
