Everything downstream of the contact point is the existing infrastructure. The only functional change is the message body that Grafana renders.
4. Why This Design
The Lambda needs json.loads(message) to succeed, so the SNS message body must be strict JSON. Because email subscribers sit on the same topic, they receive the same body; the team accepts this since all recipients are developers and the indented JSON remains readable. The subject line carries the human-readable alert title.
Hard-coding label values in the template (the earlier approach) only works for one alert rule and cannot distinguish multiple firing instances. Because roughly 260 rules share contact points and most rules do not define the full label set, the template must be generic and the Lambda must supply defaults.
5. AWS Changes (Minimal)
No new topics, queues, or subscriptions. The existing EXAMPLE-PRD-Alerts topic and example-prd-alerts-queue are reused as-is.
Recommended: enable raw message delivery on the existing SQS subscription so the Lambda receives the bare JSON body. This is a per-subscription setting and has no effect on email subscribers.
If raw message delivery cannot be enabled, keep the SNS-envelope fallback in the Lambda (Section 9) — without raw delivery, the JSON arrives as a string inside the envelope's "Message" field.
