11. Testing Steps
Create the pilot contact point from Section 6 and point the pilot rule at it.
Trigger, preview, or wait for the pilot alert to fire.
Email check: recipients receive the alert with a readable subject line and a valid, indented JSON body containing alertname and description.
Confirm the SQS record body parses: bare JSON if raw message delivery is enabled, otherwise JSON inside the SNS envelope's "Message" field.
Ask the Lambda developer to confirm json.loads succeeds and the mapped alert appears in the internal alert UI with the pilot labels.
Fire a resolved transition and confirm the internal alert updates (not duplicates) via the fingerprint.
Label-less test: temporarily point one alert rule that has no custom labels at the pilot contact point. Confirm the payload contains only alertname/grafana_folder plus annotations, and the Lambda's fallbacks still produce a sensible internal alert.
Announce to the email recipients that alert bodies will become JSON, then perform the org-wide phase in Section 6.
12. Rollout Plan
Phase 1 — Pilot. Temporary pilot contact point on the same topic; only the Airflow rule sends JSON. Validate end to end, including the email check and the label-less test.
Phase 2 — Org-wide. Replace the Message template on the shared SNS contact point(s). All ~260 alerts switch to JSON at the same moment — emails and Lambda feed alike — with no per-rule changes. Announce the email format change to recipients before flipping.
Phase 3 — Label adoption. Teams add the standard label set (Section 8) to their rules over time. Lambda fallbacks and the lookup table shrink as label coverage grows.
13. Checklist
No new AWS resources: existing topic, queue, and subscriptions reused.
Subject field of the SNS integration remains human-readable; only the Message field carries JSON.
Generic JSON template pasted into the Message field; rendered body verified as valid JSON.
Template contains no alert-specific values.
Raw message delivery enabled on the SQS subscription, or the envelope fallback kept in the Lambda.
Lambda tolerates missing labels, applies fallbacks, uses fingerprint for create/update, and skips (or dead-letters) non-JSON bodies during the transition.
Email recipients informed that alert bodies become JSON.
Pilot validated with a fully-labeled rule and a label-less rule before flipping the shared contact point(s).
